  "prompt": "Startup Law: How common is the anti-dilution provision for VCs in a Series A round?",
  "response": "Anti-dilution provisions are quite common in Series A financing rounds. Venture capitalists (VCs) frequently seek these provisions to protect their investment from being diluted in future financing rounds, particularly if the company issues new shares at a lower valuation than the previous round (known as a \"down round\").\n\nThe most common types of anti-dilution provisions are:\n\n1. **Full Ratchet:** This form provides maximum protection for investors, allowing them to convert their preferred shares into a greater number of common shares as if the new shares were issued at the lower price. It essentially keeps the investor's percentage ownership the same even after a down round.\n\n2. **Weighted Average:** This approach is more common than full ratchet. It adjusts the conversion price of preferred shares based on a formula that takes into account the number of new shares issued and their price, thereby providing a fairer adjustment than the full ratchet.\n\nWeighted average anti-dilution can come in two variations:\n\n- **Broad-based weighted average:** Involves all shares in the calculation, providing a moderate level of protection.\n- **Narrow-based weighted average:** Only considers certain shares, offering stronger protection but not as much as full ratchet.\n\nStartups and their founders should understand the implications of these provisions as they can significantly affect the value of their equity in future financing rounds. Negotiating the terms of anti-dilution protection is an important aspect of Series A agreements.",
